WEBVTT

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Ambiorix is a web framework for R. So at this point, you might be like, hmm, is this just a Shiny 2.0?

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:16.000
The answer to that is a big no. Ambiorix is neither a replacement nor an upgrade to Shiny.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:22.000
In fact, it's a fundamentally different approach to how web development is done in R.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
A little backstory on how I got into using Ambiorix.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Back in 2022, I was working for an actuarial consulting firm and we were building this Shiny application for general valuation of actuarial claims.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:46.000
The application got so huge, and by huge I mean hidden tab panels upon hidden tab panels upon hidden tab panels.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.000
And we started getting into problems.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:58.000
The first problem was I could not share a link to a specific page or section of the application.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:06.000
This meant clients would go through a lot of clicks before they got to a page or a section within the application.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.000
As a result of that, we got a second problem.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:17.000
Clients started requesting for API endpoints to our application so that they can build their own frontends.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:22.000
Now, Shiny doesn't support either multi pages or API endpoints.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
And this was a big problem.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:30.000
Now the dilemma I was in though, was I really did not want to leave the R ecosystem.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
R was the first programming language I learned and I love it.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
I just wasn't ready to ditch it.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Now, that was when I started looking for solutions and I stumbled upon Ambiorix.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Then I realized it in fact handles both of my problems, multi pages and APIs.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
I have lived happily ever since.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
At this point, you already know why you should care about Ambiorix.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:10.000
You get true multi page support, API capabilities, meaning you can create your JSON endpoints alongside the HTML pages using the same syntax.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:20.000
And a third one is that you get fine grained control over the HTTP request response cycle, which we'll talk about in a bit.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
So does it mean that you should switch from Shiny to Ambiorix?

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Let's see a comparison.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:34.000
The main difference between Shiny and Ambiorix is that with Shiny, you get batteries plugged in, all you have to do just plug and play.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:40.000
On the other hand, for Ambiorix, you have to build everything from scratch, literally.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
What does that mean?

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Shiny gives you prebuilt UI components.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Think radio buttons, action buttons, text inputs.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
You also get bootstrap and jQuery out of the box.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:00.000
And in fact, the best thing about Shiny, you get a reactive framework built in to Shiny.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
On the other hand, for Ambiorix, you have no prebuilt UI components.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
This means if you want an action button, build it.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.000
You want a text input, build it.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
You want a radio button, you guessed right, build it.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:24.000
But it also means you can use whichever frontend framework you want, whether JavaScript or CSS, go for whatever you want.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
We have no reactivity by default.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:31.000
What we do have though are HTTP requests.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:36.000
Now from that comparison, this should be your takeaway.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:41.000
The best thing about Ambiorix is also the worst thing about it.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
You get unparalleled customization.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:51.000
Just take care that you're not caught up in the customization when you should be delivering business value.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Now let's talk about the request response cycle.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.000
This is the core idea of how Ambiorix works.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:03.000
In fact, if you understand this, you'll be 50% there.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And it's in fact the core idea of how every interaction on the web works, from loading a page to submitting a form.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
This cycle is initiated by the client.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
The client sends a request to the server.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:26.000
The client in this case can basically be a web browser or another application sending a request to yourself.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:31.000
The request is basically a message detailing what the client wants.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
For example, give me the homepage.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:42.000
Now the server gets the request, processes it and gives back a response.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:47.000
The server in this case is your Ambiorix application.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Ambiorix creates a web server.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.000
That is the server that we are talking about.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:00.000
And the response that the server gives back could be the requested data, an HTML page or an action confirmation.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.000
And this cycle keeps going on and on and on.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:09.000
The client sends a request to the server and the server gives back a response.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:20.000
Now we have a small data dashboard demo that we prepared where we'll be exploring the MTKs, IRIS and air quality datasets.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:28.000
And we'll basically see that we have an HTML interface for humans and a JSON API for programmatic access.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:33.000
So let me share the demo.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
Now this is the homepage for our dashboard.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
It's a really small dashboard.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And on the homepage what we see are the available datasets and we have the API endpoints down here.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.000
So for the available datasets we of course have MTKs, IRIS and air quality.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:07:01.000
Now if you click on any of these buttons, the view dataset ones, this takes us to another page where we can see, you know, a bit of a summary about the datasets.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So this is the summary for the numeric columns in the MTKs dataset.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
And then down here we get to see the first few rows of the dataset.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:26.000
Now the thing about ambiric since it's multi-page, since you can build multi-page applications using it, it means you can use the browser's back and forward buttons and they would work as you expect.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:35.000
And if you click this one for iris, since it has categorical columns, we also get a summary of those and obviously the first few rows.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:39.000
Now the thing is, this right here, this is the HTML representation.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:44.000
This is what you want your users, the ones who visit your website to see.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:54.000
On the other hand, if we click on this button for JSON summary, now this is the same thing as the HTML representation but in JSON format.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:01.000
Now this is the JSON format, like it's the JSON representation of the page that we were just viewing.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:06.000
So you can see here we have numeric columns, categorical columns and maybe the first few rows.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:20.000
So if we can cross check the JSON summary again, if we can print this then zoom in, you can see that we have the numeric summary and then down here we will have the factor summary and finally sample data.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:27.000
And it's literally, well it's not exactly the same thing but it's the same representation in different formats.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:35.000
And that's it about the dashboard. It was a really small one so nothing huge.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:50.000
Now going back to the presentation, before we can talk about how the demo works, let's see how we can create a Hello World program using Amdrux.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:59.000
First things first, you of course load the library and then we create an app instance of an Amdrux application using Amdrux of capital A.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:09.000
And then this next section says for every get request slash the homepage, I want it to be handled by this function, this handler.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:15.000
One thing to note is that all handlers in Amdrux must take a request and a response object.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:22.000
The request object contains everything you need to know about the incoming HTTP request.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:29.000
Think cookies, content type, any headers that you have set. It will contain everything about that request.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:34.000
Then you will use the response object to well, send back responses to the client.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.000
In this case we send back a simple hello from Amdrux.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.000
We finally start the application on port 3000.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:49.000
So you've heard that this is a get request. Does it mean that there are other HTTP requests?

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:53.000
Yes, and in fact, these are the most common ones.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:59.000
So we have a get request, post request, put request and delete request.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:04.000
You will mostly use get request to retrieve a resource from the server.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:10.000
For example, when you visit posit.co, you are getting the homepage for posit.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:16.000
You will mostly use post request to create a new resource on the server.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
For example, when registering a new user in your application.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:27.000
Then you have put request which you will mostly use to update an existing resource in the server.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:32.000
A good example is for updating a user profile.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:39.000
And finally we have delete request which you will use to delete a resource from the server.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:43.000
And a good example, to delete a user account.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:47.000
It's most probably a delete request.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:52.000
So next up are the core concepts and ideas used in building the demo application.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:55.000
And I will hand this over to John.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:59.000
Thank you, Kennedy, for your presentation and the demo.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:08.000
As we said, I'll go into some of the core concepts in a bit more detail in the following slides.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:14.000
First, we'll go with this idea of a unified business logic and different response formats.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:18.000
The idea is you can centralize your business logic.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
Have one, in this case, one core R function.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
But then two interfaces with it.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:29.000
One for human consumers that want to consume a nice beautiful HTML page.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:35.000
But for your machines, you can return raw JSON.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.000
And so this is very much how it looks.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:40.000
You can centralize your business logic fairly easily.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And then the results, the data, in different ways.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
And I know this is something that you can do without MBRX.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
You can do it in R currently.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.000
You could have a central R package to hold your business logic.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
On the one end, a Shiny application.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:58.000
And on the other, a Plumber application.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
But I would argue that with MBRX, you can put everything in one place.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:06.000
It is much easier to manage, change, update, test, etc.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
So how does that look in the code?

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
Well, in MBRX, we're going to create two different routes.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
One for HTML and one for JSON.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:20.000
And you'll see that they both make use of that get dataset summary function.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:28.000
But the first creates a nice HTML page and returns that probably to a browser.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:34.000
Whereas the second, we just send it to the JSON method of MBRX.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:38.000
And we trust MBRX with serializing that correctly.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:43.000
So this is where you have one function, two different ways of presenting it.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:47.000
And you might have spotted that in the code before.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:55.000
But one very simple yet important concept with MBRX is this idea of route parameters.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:01.000
In our example, we just support three datasets.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.000
But in a real-life example, you might have a lot more than that.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:15.000
And essentially, you cannot sensibly hard-code this path and these routes manually in your code.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:21.000
But also, in many instances, as you develop these applications,

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:27.000
the routes that you are expected to serve are not known at the time you write the code.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:33.000
So we need a way to handle those dynamic URLs, which is what we have here.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:39.000
You can go to slash datasets slash empty cars or iris or air quality.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
But we have one route in the code.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:48.000
And we use this funny notation, colon name, which is, again, taken from Express.js.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:53.000
And the idea is that, without going into too much detail,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.000
essentially, the MBRX server uses that to form a regular expression

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:02.000
and correctly match your route to the request that comes in to the correct handler

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
that we have internally.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:10.000
And it will parse this route to make the parameters available to you as a nice list

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:14.000
on the request object, as is seen there on the second line.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:19.000
So I can access the name because that's how we've called it, colon name.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:23.000
We can access the name as part of that parameters list

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:28.000
and then use it downstream in our code for whatever purpose we see fit.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:34.000
So this is how you handle dynamic routes using route parameters.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:39.000
Something that's very similar to route parameters are query parameters.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
I've seen people use it interchangeably.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:47.000
You shouldn't if you want to write proper RESTful APIs.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
I think the way they're done in the demo here is correct.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:55.000
And, again, these query parameters, you may not have implemented them,

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:00.000
but I'm pretty certain you've consumed them if you've used any sort of API in the past.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:05.000
You might have, for instance, for the pagination, it's ideal.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:13.000
You might have put question mark, page equals one, page equals two, et cetera.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
Some APIs might allow you to sort the results.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
You can put sort, ascending, descending.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:23.000
You can select certain fields, perhaps, or columns in a data set.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:27.000
This is the kind of things you use the query parameters for.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.000
And they look a bit like this.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:35.000
So note that that means those are always, always optional.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.000
So if you just go to slash data, you get all the rows in the data.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:46.000
But then if you do the question mark followed by those query parameters,

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
you can get different results.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
In the demo, we just implement limit.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:59.000
You are free to implement whatever query parameters you think applies to your application.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.000
So if you pass limit equals one, you will get five rows.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
Limit equals ten, you get ten rows.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:11.000
And how it looks in the data set is in the data, in the apologies,

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
in the code is very much like this.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
Very similar to what we saw before with the parameters.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
You can still see it online too.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:23.000
As part of the request object, this time we access the query,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:31.000
which is a list, a named list with all the query parameters that the user might have passed to that URL.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:37.000
And in that case, limit, which you can again use downstream in your code for whatever purpose.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.000
Here we just, I think we just call it on head.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:46.000
You do head the data and you pass the limit and then we return that as JSON.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
Now this is somewhat fun.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Common HTTP error responses.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:55.000
You need to understand a bit more about HTTP status codes if you work with MPR.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:00.000
But one, they're very simple and two, it's kind of fun too.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:05.000
For once, return those error response codes rather than be on the receiving end of them.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:10.000
And as I said on the slide there, it's extremely important to do them properly.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:13.000
Oftentimes we can, we feel we can ignore them.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:20.000
And generally when you browse your application with a web browser, you won't notice it.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:27.000
But generally for programmatic use downstream, it's extremely important to use the right HTTP status code.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
We'll just go over three of them.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
Two 400s and one 500.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:39.000
The 400 bad requests, you might have observed that if you try to integrate or consume a web API.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.000
I certainly have.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:45.000
If I try and make a request that is incorrect, then the server can return bad requests.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:54.000
For instance, in our demo, we could imagine returning that if someone in that query uses negative limit, for instance.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:55.000
That doesn't make sense.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:56.000
That's a bad request.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
We can return that.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:17:59.000
404 not found.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:00.000
I think we've all seen that.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:05.000
You try and access a resource that doesn't exist on the server.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:09.000
And 500, that's an internal server error.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:14.000
And you might have observed that, but these HTTP error codes are classified.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:18.000
So everything that starts with a four 400 is a client error.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:22.000
Everything that starts with a five 500 is a server error.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
Two 200 is success.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
Three 300 is redirect, et cetera.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:31.000
So how could we use that, for instance, in MVRX?

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.000
Well, in our routes, we have dynamic routes.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:37.000
So people can pass the data set, empty cars, iris, or air quality.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:46.000
But what if someone thinks they can get the summary for penguins or cars or another data set that we do not support?

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:50.000
Well, in that case, the appropriate response is a 404.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
And we can do that in the code.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
You see that we check that the data set name is valid.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:19:00.000
And if it is not, we create a response that essentially says the data set is not found.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:07.000
But before we send that response, importantly, we set the correct status to 404 or not.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:11.000
And so that is it for us today.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
And we'd encourage you to try MVRX.

